omplex web of structural obstacles a low-income, physically disabled woman living in West Texas faces as she contemplates her sexual and reproductive intentions. In a period in which women’s reproductive lives are imperiled, Reproductive Justice provides an essential guide to understanding and mobilizing around women’s human rights in the twenty-first century. Reproductive Justice: A New Vision for the Twenty-First Century publishes works that explore the contours and content of reproductive justice. The series will include primers intended for students and those new to reproductive justice as well as books of original research that will further knowledge and impact society. Learn more at www.ucpress.edu/go/reproductivejustice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican American womenxHealth and hygiene. 0aHuman reproductionxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aReproductive healthzUnited States. 0aReproductive rightszUnited States. 0aWomen's rightszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh  a21st century reproductive legislation.  aabortion debate.  afeminism.  afeminist politics.  afeminists.  agender womens studies.  ahuman rights.  alow-income women.  aphysically disabled.  apolitical activists.  areproductive politics.  areproductive rights.  aroe v wade.  ascholars.  awomen of color.  awomens rights advocates.1 aSolinger, Rickie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052028818840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096320740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520963207423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/co